#PROCESSING DATA #using base R notation assing only african countries to the variable africadata ## <- right of the chosen variable name ###all african counties are accessed through the dataset gapminder by using the variable content. The accessor $ is used to access specific variables (i.e., continent) ####we then pull out the african counties by using a logical vector (i.e., ==) to determine if the variable content is listed as Africa

africadata <- gapminder$continent == "Africa"

#str - basic information on the variable #summary - statistical summaries of selected data

str(africadata)
##  logi [1:10545] FALSE TRUE TRUE FALSE FALSE FALSE ...
summary(africadata)
##    Mode   FALSE    TRUE 
## logical    7638    2907

##the results from this code chunk indicated that we have 2907 arguments that are true out of a total of 10545 ###this results in our dataset being dereased to 2908

#Now we want to define two new variables: (1) Infant_LifeExpec_Africa ~ which includes infant_mortality and life_expectency and (2) Pop_LifeExp_Africa ~ includes population and life_expectancy

#First, lets pull out just the infant_mortality data from africa #In order to do so, we call the variable infant_mortality_africa #Then, we need to access the infant mortality data within gapminder using the $ accessor and applying the logical vector (ie., []) africadata. This makes it so we only pull the infant mortality data from africa

infant_mortality_africa <- gapminder$infant_mortality[africadata]

#Lets apply the same logic to pull out the life expectancy data

life_expectency_africa <- gapminder$life_expectancy[africadata]

#now we have to seperate variables that we want to combine to make Infant_LifeExpec_Africa ##when want to combine two variables we use a dataframe #We need to define the pieces of the dataframe by using equal signs followed by the variables we created earlier

Infant_LifeExpec_Africa <- data.frame(infant_mortality = infant_mortality_africa, life_expectancy = life_expectency_africa)

#Now we need to repeat the process with a different set of variables to create Pop_LifeExp_Africa ~ includes population and life_expectancy

Population_africa <- gapminder$population[africadata]
life_expectency_africa <- gapminder$life_expectancy[africadata]

#create the dataframe #remember to name the dataframe using <- #then define parts of the dataframe using = and the dataset

Pop_LifeExp_Africa <- data.frame(population = Population_africa, life_expectency = life_expectency_africa)

#Now lets check out these new dataframes we made using the str and summary function

#Now we want to extract the data for only the year 2000 from africadata #remember that africadata contains 9 variables #first lets create an index to select for the year 2000

 yr2000 <- gapminder$year == 2000

#Now we want to use the logical operator & since we want two things to be true (i.e., from africa data AND the year 2000) #We will call this new variable africa2000

africa2000 <- yr2000 & africadata

#Now we need to apply this index to all NINE variable in the dataset to pull out the data for the year 2000 in only african countries

year2000 <- gapminder$year[africa2000]
region2000 <- gapminder$region[africa2000]
country2000 <- gapminder$country[africa2000]
infant_mortality2000 <- gapminder$infant_mortality[africa2000]
life_expectency2000 <- gapminder$life_expectancy[africa2000]
fertility2000 <- gapminder$fertility[africa2000]
gdp2000 <- gapminder$gdp[africa2000]
continent2000 <- gapminder$continent[africa2000]
population2000 <- gapminder$population[africa2000]

#phew, pulled them all out

#now we need to create a new dataframe using all the new variable names we created above that single out african countries in the year 2000

africa2000_df <- data.frame(year = year2000, region = region2000, country = country2000, infant_mortality = infant_mortality2000, life_expectency = life_expectency2000, fertility = fertility2000, gdp = gdp2000, continent= continent2000, population = population2000)

#MORE PLOTTING #Now we are going to make the two previous plots again, however only using the data from the year 2000 #first lets plot infant mortality and life expectency in africa for the yr 2000

plot(infant_mortality2000, life_expectency2000)

#we see a negative correlation

#plot population size and life expectancy for the year 2000 in africa #first define the population to a log10 scale

log10pop_yr2000 <- log10(population2000)
plot(log10pop_yr2000, life_expectency2000)

#no noticeable correlation

#A SIMPLE FIT #Use the lm function (linear model function - used to create a simple regression model) and fit life expectancy at the outcome (y variable), and infant mortality as the predictor (x variable) #the summary function gives us various statistics indlucding residuals, coefficents,

lm1 <- lm(life_expectency2000 ~ infant_mortality2000)
summary(lm1)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = life_expectency2000 ~ infant_mortality2000)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max

## F-statistic: 43.48 on 1 and 49 DF,  p-value: 2.826e-08

#linear regression model for life expectancy (y) and population size as the predictor # a p value of 2.826e-08 suggests that these are related as the P value is very small

lm2 <- lm(life_expectency2000 ~ log10pop_yr2000)
summary(lm2)
## 
## Call:

#P value of 0.4755. A p value this size suggests the variables are not related (i.e., population size does not affect life expectancy)

#we can also visualise this fit line on the scatterplot using the abline function

plot(infant_mortality2000, life_expectency2000)
abline(lm1)

#this is nice because it resolidifies the conclusions i came to before

plot(log10pop_yr2000, life_expectency2000)
abline(lm2)
